1 Task 1: Data Source

This is survey data collected by the US National Center for Health Statistics (NCHS) which has conducted a series of health and nutrition surveys since the early 1960s. Since 1999 approximately 5,000 individuals of all ages are interviewed in their homes every year and complete the health examination component of the survey. The health examination is conducted in a mobile examination centre (MEC).

The NHANES target population is the non-institutionalized civilian resident population of the United States. NHANES, (American National Health and Nutrition Examination surveys), use complex survey designs (see http://www.cdc.gov/nchs/data/series/sr_02/sr02_162.pdf) that oversample certain subpopulations like racial minorities. Naive analysis of the original NHANES data can lead to mistaken conclusions. The percentages of people from each racial group in the data, for example, are quite different from the way they are in the population.

NHANES and NHANESraw each include 75 variables available for the 2009-2010 and 2011-2012 sample years. NHANESraw has 20,293 observations of these variables plus four additional variables that describe that sample weighting scheme employed. NHANES contains 10,000 rows of data resampled from NHANESraw to undo these oversampling effects. NHANES can be treated, for educational purposes, as if it were a simple random sample from the American population.

2 Task 2: Load and Tidy the Data

n_h <- 
  data("NHANES")

As originally loaded, the n_h data contain Weight colums and Height columns are found at http://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nhanes/nhanes2011-2012/BMX_G.htm. Depressed columns is found at http://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nhanes/nhanes2011-2012/HDL_G.htm. Gender colums and Age columns are found at http://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nhanes/nhanes2011-2012/DEMO_G.htm. HardDrugs colums and Alcoholday columns are found at http://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nhanes/nhanes2011-2012/SMQ_G.htm.Explanations of each of the original variables in the NHANES set.

2.1 Tidying, Data Cleaning and Data Management

There are several things going on in the next bit of code, which maintains the original as-imported data as n_h but creates a new tibble called pro1.

pro1 <- NHANES %>%
   filter(SurveyYr == "2011_12") %>%
   filter(Age >= 25 & Age <= 46) %>%
   mutate(Sex = Gender, 
          Race = Race1,
          income = HHIncome,
          drugs = HardDrugs,
          alcohol = AlcoholDay,
          Sex = fct_relevel(Sex,"male", "female"),
          Depressed = fct_relevel(Depressed, "Most", "Several", 
                                         "None"),
          Race = fct_relevel(Race, "Black", "White", 
                                   "Mexican", "Hispanic", "Other"),
          drugs = fct_relevel(drugs, "Yes")) %>%
   select( ID, Sex, Age, Weight,Race, Height, Depressed,income,drugs,alcohol)

2.1.1 Change the name of HHIncomeMid to income,HardDrugs to drugs,Gender to Sex and AlcoholDay to alcohol.

Relevant code:

   mutate(Sex = Gender, 
          Race = Race1,
          income = HHIncome,
          drugs = HardDrugs,
          alcohol = AlcoholDay)

2.1.2 Re-ordering the levels of the categorical variables

In my opinion, for Depressed, well change the order to(Most, Several,None).

Relevant code:

   Sex = fct_relevel(pro1$Sex,"male", "female")
   Depressed = fct_relevel(pro1$Depressed, "Most", "Several", 
                                         "None")
   Race = fct_relevel(pro1$Race, "Black", "White", 
                                   "Mexican", "Hispanic", "Other")

Now, I will reorder the No/Yes factor as Yes/No instead because the drugs variables have No listed before Yes in this output.

  drugs = fct_relevel(pro1$drugs, "Yes")

After that, there is no missing data.

4 Task 4: Code Book

The 10 variables in our tidy data set for this demonstration are as follows.

Variable Type Description / Levels
ID Quantitative subject code (62172-71847)
Sex Categorical Male or Female
Age Quantitative age of subject: 25 - 47
Race Categorical Mexican, Hispanic, White, Black, Asian, or Other
Height Quantitative Standing height in cm
Weight Quantitative Weight in kg
income Quantitative Numerical version of HHIncome derived from the middle income in each category
Depressed Categorical participants aged 18 years or older. One of None, Several, Majority (more than half the days), or AlmostAll
drugs Categorical Participant has tried cocaine, crack cocaine, heroin or methamphetamine. Reported for participants aged 18 to 69 years as Yes or No
alcohol Quantitative Average number of drinks consumed on days that participant drank alcoholic beverages

5 Task 5: My Subjects

These data take from NHANES each include 75 variables available for 2011-2012 sample years, and NHANES contains 10,000 rows of data resampled from NHANESraw to undo these oversampling effects. NHANES, (American National Health and Nutrition Examination surveys), use complex survey designs (see http://www.cdc.gov/nchs/data/series/sr_02/sr02_162.pdf) that oversample certain subpopulations like racial minorities. I take 10 variables from 75 variables, which is ID,Age, Sex,Race, Weight, Height,Depressed, HHIncomeMid,HardDrugs and AlcoholDay. I randomly take range of age which is 25-47 because no one could give a clear definition of Middle-age. Therefore, I get the 975 subjects in the pro1_tidy dataset.

I use ID,Age, Sex,Race, Weight, Height,Depressed, HHIncomeMid to predict the binary outcome HardDrugs and the quantitative outcome AlcoholDay.

6 Task 6: My Variables

  1. ID
    • This is a patient identification code, ranging from 62172-71847.
  2. Age
    • This is the patients age at baseline in years (baseline = the time when they underwent dobutamine stress echocardiography.)
  3. Sex
    • This is an indicator (female or male) of the patients sex.
  4. Race
    • This is the patients race.Included Mexican, Hispanic, White, Black, or Other(other & Asian)
  5. Weight
    • This is the patients Weight in kg.
  6. Height
    • This is the patients Standing height in cm.
  7. Depressed
    • The self-reported number of days where participant felt down, depressed or hopeless. One of None, Several, Majority (more than half the days), or AlmostAll.
  8. income
    • Total annual gross income for the household in US dollars. One of 0 - 4999, 5000 - 9,999, 10000 - 14999, 15000 - 19999, 20000 - 24,999, 25000 - 34999, 35000 - 44999, 45000 - 54999, 55000 - 64999, 65000 - 74999, 75000 - 99999, or 100000 or More. Numerical version of HHIncome derived from the middle income in each category.
  9. alcohol
    • Average number of drinks consumed on days that participant drank alcoholic beverages.
  10. drugs
    • This indicates whether the participant has tried cocaine, crack cocaine, heroin or methamphetamine as (yes or no).

10.1 Model A. Modified Kitchen Sink

Lets start with a model including just four of our candidate predictors, including an interaction between Sex and Weight and then main effects for Race and the other four candidate predictors.

d <- datadist(pro1_tidy)

               Depressed + income + Age ,

10.2.1 Imputation Model

Ill build the imputation model using my outcome, and the variables with at least one missing value, in this case.

f.A <- aregImpute(~ Height + Weight + income,

10.3.1 Building the Four Summary Plots

best_mods_1 <- data_frame( k = 2:8,
                           r2 = rs$rsq, adjr2 = rs$adjr2, cp = rs$cp, aic.c = rs$aic.c, bic = rs$bic)
rs <- cbind(best_mods_1, rs$which)
p1<- ggplot(rs, aes(x = k, y = adjr2,label = round(adjr2,2))) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_label() +
  geom_label(data = subset(rs,adjr2 == max(adjr2)),aes(x = k, y = adjr2, label = round(adjr2,2)),
             fill = "yellow", col = "blue") + theme_bw() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 2:8) +
  labs(x = "# of predictors (including intercept)",y = "Adjusted R-squared")

p2<- ggplot(rs, aes(x = k, y = cp,
                   label = round(cp,1))) +
  geom_line() +geom_label() +geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1,col = "red") + theme_bw() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 2:8) +
  labs(x = "# of predictors (including intercept)",y = "Mallows' Cp")

p3<- ggplot(rs, aes(x = k, y = aic.c,label = round(aic.c,1))) +geom_line() +
  geom_label() +geom_label(data = subset(rs, aic.c == min(aic.c)),aes(x = k, y = aic.c), fill = "pink",
                           col = "red") + theme_bw() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 2:8) +labs(x = "# of predictors (including intercept)",y = "Bias-Corrected AIC")

p4<- ggplot(rs, aes(x = k, y = bic,label = round(bic,1))) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_label() +
  geom_label(data = subset(rs, bic == min(bic)),aes(x = k, y = bic),fill = "lightgreen", col = "blue") + theme_bw() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 2:8) +
  labs(x = "# of predictors (including intercept)",y = "BIC")
gridExtra::grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, p4, nrow = 2)
